code:
To find $T \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 9 \\ 12 \end{pmatrix},$ we will first find $\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 9 \\ 12 \end{pmatrix}$ as a linear combination of $\begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ 6 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\begin{pmatrix} -6 \\ 3 \\ 6 \end{pmatrix}.$ To do this, we want to find $a$ and $b$ such that 
\[(a) \begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ 6 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} + (b)\begin{pmatrix} -6 \\ 3 \\ 6 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 9 \\ 12 \end{pmatrix}.\]
The linear system associated with the above vector equation consists of
\begin{align*} 6a-6b&=3\\
6a+3b&=9\\
3a+6b&=12
\end{align*} Subtracting the two equations from each other, we get 
\begin{align*} 6a-6b&=3\\
6(a-b)&=3\\
\Rightarrow \qquad a-b&=1/2\\
&\\
6a+3b&=9\\
-7b&=-12\\
\Rightarrow \qquad b&=12/7\\
&\\
\text{Substitute b into } a-b&=1/2\\
a - 12/7&=1/2\\
\Rightarrow \qquad a&=(12/7) + (1/2)\\
&=(12+7)/14\\
&=19/14.
\end{align*}Since we have 
\begin{align*} \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 9 \\ 12 \end{pmatrix}&= (19/14)\begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ 6 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} + (-12/7)\begin{pmatrix} -6 \\ 3 \\ 6 \end{pmatrix} \end{align*}
By property $(i)$, we get 
\begin{align*} T \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 9 \\ 12 \end{pmatrix} &= (19/14)T\begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ 6 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} + (-12/7)T\begin{pmatrix} -6 \\ 3 \\ 6 \end{pmatrix}\\
&= (19/14)\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -1 \\ 8 \end{pmatrix} + (-12/7)\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 8 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}
Now,
\begin{align*}
&= (19/14)\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -1 \\ 8 \end{pmatrix} + (-12/7)\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 8 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}\\
&= (19/14) \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -1 \\ 8 \end{pmatrix} - (24/14)\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 8 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}\\
&= (19/14) \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -1 \\ 8 \end{pmatrix} - (12/7)\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 8 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}\\
&= (19/14)\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -1 \\ 8 \end{pmatrix} + (-\frac{12}{7} - \frac{24}{14}) \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 8 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}\\
&= (19/14)\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -1 \\ 8 \end{pmatrix} + (-\frac{12}{7} - \frac{12}{7}) \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 8 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}\\
&= (19/14)\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -1 \\ 8 \end{pmatrix} + (-\frac{24}{7}) \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 8 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}\\
&= (19/14 + (-24/7)) \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 8 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}\\
&= \frac{19-48}{14
\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ -16 \\ 52 \end{pmatrix}}
To get the above answer, we  need to compute
\begin{align*} \frac{19-48}{14} \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 8 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} &= (-29/14) \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 8 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}\\
&= (-29/14) \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 8 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}/(1)\\
&= (-29/14) \begin{pmatrix} 4+8-1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}/(1)\\
&= (-29/14) \begin{pmatrix} -7 \\ 11 \\ -11 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}
Multiplying in vector form:
\begin{align*} (-29/14) \begin{pmatrix} -7 \\ 11 \\ -11 \end{pmatrix}&=(29/14) \begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ -11 \\ 11 \end{pmatrix}\\
&= (29/2) \begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ -22 \\ 22 \end{pmatrix}/(7)\\
&= (29/2) \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -11/7 \\ 11/7 \end{pmatrix}/(7)\\
&= (-29) \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -11/7 \\ 11/7 \end{pmatrix}/(14)
\end{align*}
Multiplying in vector form by taking the negative for both the numerator and denominator: 
\begin{align*} (-29) \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -11/7 \\ 11/7 \end{pmatrix}/(14)&=(-1)(-29) \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -11/7 \\ 11/7 \end{pmatrix}/(-1)(14)\\
&=(-1) \begin{pmatrix} -29 \\ 29(11/7) \\ -29(11/7) \end{pmatrix}\\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 29 \\ -319/7 \\ 319/7 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}
Using the property $(ii)$ and that the cross product of vectors is perpendicular to the vectors, the first vector gets a $0$ in its $y$ component and the second vector gets a $0$ in its $x$ component, when we take cross product.
Using the property of cross product we get following vector:
\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 9 \\ 12 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} -6 \\ 3 \\ 6 \end{pmatrix}&=
\begin{vmatrix}
\hat{i} & \hat{j} & \hat{k}\\
3 & 9 & 12\\
-6 & 3 & 6
\end{vmatrix}\\
&=\hat{i}(54-36) - \hat{j}(18-(-72)) + \hat{k}(9-(-54))\\
&=\hat{i}18 - 90\hat{j} + 63\hat{k}
\end{align*}
Multiply the expression by $-12/7$
\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 9 \\ 12 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} -6 \\ 3 \\ 6 \end{pmatrix}&= (-12/7)\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 9 \\ 12 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} -6 \\ 3 \\ 6 \end{pmatrix}\\
&= (-12/7)\begin{vmatrix}
\hat{i} & \hat{j} & \hat{k}\\
3 & 9 & 12\\
-6 & 3 & 6
